Package org.neo4j.internal.batchimport.staging

Class ProcessorStep<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.neo4j.internal.batchimport.staging.AbstractStep<T>
      • org.neo4j.internal.batchimport.staging.ProcessorStep<T>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    AutoCloseable, Parallelizable, Panicable, Step<T>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    CacheGroupsStep, CountGroupsStep, EncodeGroupsStep, LabelIndexWriterStep, NodeSetFirstGroupStep, ReadRecordsStep, RecordProcessorStep, RelationshipTypeIndexWriterStep, UpdateRecordsStep
    public abstract class ProcessorStep<T>
extends AbstractStep<T>
    Step that uses TaskExecutor as a queue and execution mechanism. Supports an arbitrary number of threads to execute batches in parallel. Subclasses implement process(Object, BatchSender, PageCursorTracer) receiving the batch to process and an BatchSender for sending the modified batch, or other batches downstream.

      • process

        protected abstract void process​(T batch,
                                BatchSender sender,
                                PageCursorTracer cursorTracer)
                         throws Throwable
        Processes a received batch. Any batch that should be sent downstream as part of processing the supplied batch should be done so using BatchSender.send(Object). The most typical implementation of this method is to process the received batch, either by creating a new batch object containing some derivative of the received batch, or the batch object itself with some modifications and emit that in the end of the method.
        Parameters:
        batch - batch to process.
        sender - BatchSender for sending zero or more batches downstream.
        cursorTracer - underlying page cursor tracer
        Throws:
        Throwable

      • processors

        public int processors​(int delta)
        Description copied from interface: Parallelizable
        Change number of processors assigned to this Parallelizable. Accepts a delta, which may specify positive or negative value, even zero. This instances may have internal constraints in the number of processors, min or max, which may be assigned and so potentially the change will only be partially accepted or not at all. This is why this call returns the total number of processors this instance now has accepted after any effect of this call. Parallelizable is used in many call stacks where call delegation is predominant and so reducing number of methods to delegate is favored. This is why this method looks and functions like this, it can cater for incrementing, decrementing and even getting number of processors.
        Parameters:
        delta - number of processors to add or remove, i.e. negative or positive value. A value of zero will result in merely the current number of assigned processors to be returned.
        Returns:
        the number of assigned processors as a result this call.
